posts.name: Goktug Yildiz
posts.cooked: I am trying to make a driver station for our team. And I have no idea where to start or how to do it can anyone guide me please?

posts.name: Jade
posts.cooked: You cannot make a custom driver station you are required to use the NI driver station for competitions. If you would like to create one for your own personal use it is possible but very difficult so you should be reasonably experienced before attempting it

Are you taking about a physical driver station that is used to carry computers and joysticks for the drive team or the app. If you are talking about the app I agree with @spacey_sooty that it will be very difficult and not very useful.

posts.name: Ana Rodriguez
posts.cooked:
So I was actually just in your shoes, trying to make a new driver station for our team that I can carry around during comps (assuming you mean what you carry your laptops and controllers in).

So this was our last one. It was CNC’d and powder coated to have a sleek and flashy design (the LED’s help haha). However, it was a bit of a problem because it required two hands to carry, didn’t have handles, could leave wicked scratches on people, and had no secure spot for our Xbox controllers that we used to drive… (we had a problem with them getting knocked and broken). IMG_0956_Original 1920×1440 358 KB

IMG_0956_Original 1920×1440 358 KB

IMG_0956_Original 1920×1440 358 KB

Moving forward, we just adopted/created this station. It is a simple weatherproof case but it’s been super convenient. I can carry it with one hand and set it on the ground if needed, and it provides peace of mind that everything is protected when transporting to and from (and around) an event. There’s a polycarb lining on the bottom so we don’t have to stress about the computer overheating on the foam. We’re even looking into getting some stickers or decals on it so we can get our flashy-ness back IMG_8250 1920×2560 507 KB (If you want to buy something like it: here’s the link

IMG_8250 1920×2560 507 KB

IMG_8250 1920×2560 507 KB

I recommend looking into some factors when deciding what you want, like:

Do your controllers need to be secured and/or encased?

Who will be carrying this? And will they be carrying it very far?

Velcro everything…… bottom of the station and laptop

Will something happen if the station gets hit? Will it close?

Can you pack it up quickly when the match ends?

(In our case) will the computer have to be monitored for overheating?

Can you access all the ports on the computer? Does it have to be risen up?

posts.name: Brett B Bonner
posts.cooked:
nuclearnerd:

a better name for the physical thing.

The manual says the OPERATOR CONSOLE is the “physical thing”: “the set of COMPONENTS and MECHANISMS used by the DRIVERS and/or HUMAN PLAYERS to relay commands to the ROBOT”.  This seems pretty clear.  However many people call this this “driver station” which certainly is unnecessarily confusing!

nuclearnerd:

According to the game manual, the “Driver Station” is neither of those thing, it’s a segment of the field border!

The DRIVER STATION is the section of ALLIANCE WALL behind which the drive team operates the robot.  The “Driver Station Software” isn’t an UPPERCASE DEFINED word but is specified in section 5.9: “When a DRIVE TEAM connects the Ethernet cable from their assigned DRIVER STATION to their OPERATOR CONSOLE, the Driver Station Software on the OPERATOR CONSOLE computer communicates with FMS .”

To @goktugyldz , with a bit of searching on CD you will find examples of many kinds and styles of operator console that might serve as inspiration.  Here’s ours , for instance.  Different teams prefer different approaches, from “just a laptop and controller” all the way up to very large and complex assemblies.  I suggest you talk with others on your team and define the requirements you’re trying to meet before you get too deeply into design.
